A different path opened when I picked Canva for building the digital literacy infographic. Its wide collection of templates made for students shaped that choice. The way elements snap into place with a click kept things smooth. Instead of wrestling design software, attention stayed where it mattered - on how ideas flow across the page.
A fresh start in college brings new challenges, so my infographic steps in to help. Not just decoration - it breaks down what matters most at the beginning. Three ideas carry the whole thing: understanding digital literacy, staying safe online, later handling emails like a pro. Instead of clutter, white space leads the eye through separate zones. Up front, digital know-how gets called a must-have, something you can’t do without today. Further down, small pictures shout out smart moves - think two-step logins every time. Near the end, short pointers line up practical habits, one after another. Subject lines that mean business appear there, also how to open messages right. Each piece connects without crowding the next. The look stays sharp by keeping things apart yet linked. No extras, nothing flashy, only what helps move forward. This is where clarity wins over noise.
What stood out most while designing came down to showing data clearly. Packing something detailed - like how to stay safe online - into brief tips for one slide proved tough, especially when avoiding a messy layout. Cutting back helped. A single symbol sometimes speaks quicker than many sentences. This made clear: simplicity wins in digital messages.
